<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-594-123  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 594 123.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Telephony  Oct 29 1990 v219 n19 p38(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>What cost local loop fiber? (telephone systems) (includes related'For further reading' bibliography.)andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Nelson, Cal.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Studies indicate that fiber optic technology is becomingcost-competitive with copper for plain old telephone services(POTS).andP;  Many factors must be considered when comparing theeconomics of copper and fiber.andP;  Installed first cost is probablythe most significant factor, but depreciation, maintenance costsand the ability to provide services to initial residents whiledeferring the cost of providing services to future residents canalso have major effects on the economics of systems.andP;  Fasteraccess to information is becoming more valuable, which of coursefavors fiber, and this relates to a comparison of the useful lifeof copper versus fiber.andP;  Copper's useful life will end when it canno longer deliver the high-bandwidth services that people want.andO;With costs approaching parity, telcos can expect to acceleratebuilding a fiber infrastructure, which promises many new, improvedservices.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Fiber opticsTelephone systemsTelecommunicationsTelephone companiesCost of Communications.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraphchart.andO;Caption:   Installed first costs. (graph)Costs per line vs. lines per subscriber. (graph)System architectures. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>